/a> of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/=
Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"23" alt=3D"J"> is the Jacobian determ=
inant (confusingly, often called "the
 Jacobian" as well) and is denoted
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Jacobian/NumberedEquation4.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"135" height=3D=
"41" alt=3D" J=3D|(partial(y_1,...,y_n))/(partial(x_1,...,x_n))|. "></td><t=
d align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn4" class=3D"eqnum">
(4)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
The Jacobian matrix and determinant can be computed in the <a href=3D"http:=
//www.wolfram.com/language/">Wolfram
Language</a> using =20
</p>
<pre>  JacobianMatrix[f_List?VectorQ, x_List] :=3D Outer[D, f, x]
  JacobianDeterminant[f_List?VectorQ, x_List] :=3D Det[JacobianMatrix[f, x]=
]</pre>
<p>
Taking the differential
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Jacobian/NumberedEquation5.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"82" height=3D"=
21" alt=3D" dy=3Dy_(x)dx "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn5" class=3D"eqnum">
(5)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
shows that <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacob=
ian/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"21" alt=3D"J">
 is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Determinant.html">determin=
ant</a> of the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Matrix.html">matrix=
</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/In=
line8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%"=
 border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"22" alt=3D"y_(x)">, and therefore give=
s the ratios
 of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inl=
ine9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" =
border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">-dimensional volumes (<a h=
ref=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Content.html">contents</a>)
 in <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inl=
ine10.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%"=
 border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"y"> and <img src=3D"https://=
mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inline11.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9=
" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x">,
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Jacobian/NumberedEquation6.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"282" height=3D=
"41" alt=3D" dy_1...dy_n=3D|(partial(y_1,...,y_n))/(partial(x_1,...,x_n))|d=
x_1...dx_n. "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn6" class=3D"eqnum">
(6)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
It therefore appears, for example, in the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolf=
ram.com/ChangeofVariablesTheorem.html">change
of variables theorem</a>.
</p>
<p>
The concept of the Jacobian can also be applied to <img src=3D"https://math=
world.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inline12.svg" class=3D"inlinefo=
rmula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" he=
ight=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> functions in more than <img src=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inline13.svg" class=3D"inlineformula=
" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=
=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> variables. For example, considering <img src=3D"https://=
mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inline14.svg" class=3D"inli=
neformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"7=
5" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f(u,v,w)"> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inline15.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"73" height=3D"21"=
 alt=3D"g(u,v,w)">, the Jacobians
</p>
<div class=3D"table-responsive-noborders">
<table align=3D"center" width=3D"100%" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" =
style=3D"padding-left: 50px" border=3D"0">
<tbody><tr style=3D""><td align=3D"right" width=3D""><img src=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inline16.svg" class=3D"displa=
yformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"55=
" height=3D"42" alt=3D"(partial(f,g))/(partial(u,v))"></td><td align=3D"cen=
ter" width=3D"14"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equation=
s/Jacobian/Inline17.svg" class=3D"displayformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;=
max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"20" alt=3D"=3D"></td><t=
d align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations=
/Jacobian/Inline18.svg" class=3D"displayformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"48" height=3D"53" alt=3D"|f_u f_v; g_u=
 g_v|"></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"10">
<div id=3D"eqn7" class=3D"eqnum">
(7)
</div>
</td></tr><tr style=3D""><td align=3D"right" width=3D""><img src=3D"https:/=
/mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/Inline19.svg" class=3D"dis=
playformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D=
"55" height=3D"42" alt=3D"(partial(f,g))/(partial(u,w))"></td><td align=3D"=
center" width=3D"14"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equat=
ions/Jacobian/Inline20.svg" class=3D"displayformula" style=3D"max-height:10=
0%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"20" alt=3D"=3D"></td=
><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equati=
ons/Jacobian/Inline21.svg" class=3D"displayformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"51" height=3D"53" alt=3D"|f_u f_w; =
g_u g_w|"></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"10">
<div id=3D"eqn8" class=3D"eqnum">
(8)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
can be defined (Kaplan 1984, p.&nbsp;99).
</p>
<p>
For the case of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
Jacobian/Inline22.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D3">
 variables, the Jacobian takes the special form
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Jacobian/NumberedEquation7.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"249" height=3D=
"41" alt=3D" Jf(x_1,x_2,x_3)=3D|(partialy)/(partialx_1)=C2=B7(partialy)/(pa=
rtialx_2)=C3=97(partialy)/(partialx_3)|, "></td><td align=3D"right" width=
=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn9" class=3D"eqnum">
(9)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Jacobian/I=
nline23.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"29" height=3D"21" alt=3D"a=C2=B7b"> is the <a href=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DotProduct.html">dot
 product</a> and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations=
/Jacobian/Inline24.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"35" height=3D"21" alt=3D"b=C3=97c">
 is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/CrossProduct.html">cross p=
roduct</a>, which can be expanded to give
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/Jacobian/NumberedEquation8.svg" class=3D"numberedequation" st=
yle=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"201" height=3D=
"101" alt=3D" |(partial(y_1,y_2,y_3))/(partial(x_1,x_2,x_3))|=3D|(partialy_=
1)/(partialx_1) (partialy_1)/(partialx_2) (partialy_1)/(partialx_3); (parti=
aly_2)/(partialx_1) (partialy_2)/(partialx_2) (partialy_2)/(partialx_3); (p=
artialy_3)/(partialx_1) (partialy_3)/(partialx_2) (partialy_3)/(partialx_3)=
|. "></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn10" class=3D"eqnum">
(10)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
